result.execSummary:
The defendant Tara L Weiss was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess w/Intent-Heroin (<=3g) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(d)1.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Defendant shall be immediatly eligable for programming (CIP/SAP) without limitations.

superMiscConds.notes: If a Wisconsin State Prison sentence is imposed, outstanding financial obligations shall be paid from all inmate money at a rate of 25% and the balance due as a condition of extended supervision.  If extended supervision is revoked or will discharge with financial obligations owing, a judgment shall be entered.
Defendant shall obtain and maintain either full time employment, full time school, or a combitnation of employment and schooling equal to full time status.

Defendant shall not possess or consume any controlled substances.

Defendant shallnot associate with any known drug dealers, users, or be present where drugs are illegally purchased, sold, or consumed.

Defendant shall have absolutely no contact with K.A.K., M.W.T. or any Hartford School District properties.

Defendant shall have no contact with the co-defendant except as allowed by the agent.

Defendant shall participate in all counseling and/or treatment programs directed by the probation agent.

Defendant shall participate in an AODA assessment and follow through with any treatment recommendations. 

Defendant shall provide a biological specimen for DNA analysis.  Defendant has the right to request expungement of DNA analysis in writing through the Department of Justice.

Defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety.

Defendant shall take medications only as prescribed.  

Defendant shall notify health care providers of addiction history.

Defendant shall designate one pharmacy for filling all prescriptions.

Defendant shall notify agent within 48 hours of being prescribed medications.
